Report

Time series models like ARIMA and Holt-Winters are used often for forecasting. In this report, both models will be used to forecast mean daily sunshine duration in Singapore.

Analysis

#read data
sunshine <- read.csv("NEA-sunshine-duration-monthly-mean-daily-duration.csv")
head(sunshine,13)
##      month mean_sunshine_hrs
## 1  1982-01               5.6
## 2  1982-02               7.6
## 3  1982-03               5.1
## 4  1982-04               4.7
## 5  1982-05               5.8
## 6  1982-06               7.3
## 7  1982-07               7.6
## 8  1982-08               5.4
## 9  1982-09               5.2
## 10 1982-10               5.6
## 11 1982-11               5.8
## 12 1982-12               3.3
## 13 1983-01               4.3
#create time series
sunshine_ts <- ts(sunshine[,2], start = 1982, frequency = 12)

#plot
plot(sunshine_ts)

#looks like an additive model, with trend and seasonality

plot(decompose(sunshine_ts))

Holt-Winters

#create holt-winters model
sunshine_hw <- HoltWinters(sunshine_ts)

#plot model
plot(sunshine_hw, xlim=c(2000,2020))

#forecast
library(forecast)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'xts':
##   method     from
##   as.zoo.xts zoo
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
## Registered S3 methods overwritten by 'forecast':
##   method             from    
##   fitted.fracdiff    fracdiff
##   residuals.fracdiff fracdiff

sunshine_hwf <- forecast(sunshine_hw, h = 12)
plot(sunshine_hwf, include = 50)

#acf & pacf
res <- sunshine_hwf$residuals[!is.na(sunshine_hwf$residuals)]
acf(res, lag.max = 20)

pacf(res, lag.max = 20)

#Many autocorrelations are close to significance lines(blue lines). Not a good sign.

#Ljung-Box Test
Box.test(res,type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  res
## X-squared = 3.8839, df = 1, p-value = 0.04875
#p-value <0.05 Null hypothesis(no correlation) is rejected. There is autocorrelation in model.

#Histogram (check for normal distribution)
hist(res, breaks = 50)
abline(v = mean(res), col = "blue", lwd = 3)

#looks normally distributed, mean of residuals is close to zero

#Plot Residuals (check for constant variance)
plot(res, type = "p")
abline(h=0, col = "blue")

#variance is constant, great!

While there are some autocorrelations in the Holt-Winters model, subsequent histogram plot show that mean of residuals is close to zero and residuals are normally distributed. That suggests that most of the useful information from the time series has been utilized in the model. Also, the residuals have constant variance with the exception of 2 points. Thus, this model is valid.

ARIMA

#adf test
library(tseries)
adf.test(sunshine_ts, k=12)
## Warning in adf.test(sunshine_ts, k = 12): p-value smaller than printed p-
## value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  sunshine_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -4.2468, Lag order = 12, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#p=0.01 is good news, p<0.05 means that ts is stationary

# create ARIMA model
sunshine_A <- auto.arima(sunshine_ts)
sunshine_A
## Series: sunshine_ts 
## ARIMA(2,0,1)(2,0,0)[12] with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ma1    sar1    sar2    mean
##       1.1858  -0.2453  -0.9591  0.3527  0.0835  5.6599
## s.e.  0.0575   0.0486   0.0387  0.0485  0.0530  0.0621
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 1.136:  log likelihood=-668.09
## AIC=1350.18   AICc=1350.44   BIC=1378.98
plot(sunshine_ts, xlim=c(2000,2020))
lines(sunshine_A$fitted, col="red")

#forecast
plot(forecast(sunshine_A, h = 12), include = 50)

#acf & pacf
acf(sunshine_A$residuals, lag.max = 20)

pacf(sunshine_A$residuals, lag.max = 20)

#2 points are outside of the significance boundaries. There is some autocorrelation

#Ljung-Box Test
Box.test(sunshine_A$residuals, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  sunshine_A$residuals
## X-squared = 0.0045556, df = 1, p-value = 0.9462
#p-value >0.05, in fact very high. No autocorrelation

#Histogram (check for normal distribution)
hist(sunshine_A$residuals, breaks = 40)
abline(v = mean(sunshine_A$residuals), col = "blue", lwd = 3)

#looks normally distributed, and mean is 0. Great!

#plot residuals (check for constant variance)
plot(sunshine_A$residuals, type = "p", ylim=c(-5,5))
abline(h=0, col="blue")

#variance is fairly constant

The residuals of the ARIMA model shows that the model is valid. There is some autocorrelation but it is not significant. Also, the histogram plot shows that the residuals have a mean of zero and is normally distributed. There is also constant variance.

Comparison

#models
plot(sunshine_hw, xlim=c(1985,2020), main="Models against actual observations")
lines(sunshine_A$fitted, col="blue")
legend("bottomright", legend=c("Actual","Holt-Winters","ARIMA"), col=c("black","red","blue"), lwd=1, cex = 0.7)

It seems before year 2000, Holt-Winters performs worse than ARIMA. However, after year 2000, Holt-Winters models the observations better than ARIMA. At a glance, Holt-Winters seem to be better at modelling the big variations, while ARIMA appears to be more conservative in the modelling. Since big variations are common in past observations, the Holt-Winters model is more appropriate for forecasting mean sunshine duration than the ARIMA model.

#forecasts
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(sunshine_hwf, include = 30, main="Holt-Winters Forecast")
plot(forecast(sunshine_A, h = 12), include = 30, main="ARIMA Forecast")

acf(res, lag.max = 20)
pacf(res, lag.max = 20)
#Many autocorrelations are close to significance lines(blue lines). Not a good sign.

#Ljung-Box Test
Box.test(res,type = "Ljung-Box")
#p-value <0.05 Null hypothesis(no correlation) is rejected. There is autocorrelation in model.

#Histogram (check for normal distribution)
hist(res, breaks = 50)
abline(v = mean(res), col = "blue", lwd = 3)
#looks normally distributed, mean of residuals is close to zero

#Plot Residuals (check for constant variance)
plot(res, type = "p")
abline(h=0, col = "blue")
#variance is constant, great!

#ARIMA
#adf test
library(tseries)
adf.test(sunshine_ts, k=12)
#p=0.01 is good news, p<0.05 means that ts is stationary

# create ARIMA model

sunshine_A

#forecast

pacf(sunshine_A$residuals, lag.max = 20)
#2 points are outside of the significance boundaries. There is some autocorrelation

#p-value >0.05, in fact very high. No autocorrelation

#Histogram (check for normal distribution)

Summary

Referring to the decomposed time series graph, it appears that there is a long term seasonal cycle going on in the trend component which spans roughly 20 years from 1980 to 2000 and from 2000 to 2020. At a glance, the second cycle from 2000 onwards looks to have higher peaks and less significant troughs. This means the daily sunshine duration is slowly but steady increasing.
An increase in sunshine duration would also mean more sunlight on the ground, which in turn brings about more heat(higher temperatures). This is a major concern as higher temperatures could have many detrimental effects on the environment both directly and indirectly. Singapore is feeling the effects of a warmer Earth right now, in the form of rising sea levels and intense heat waves for example. Hence, it is very important for action to be taken immediately to alleviate and attempt to slow down the effects of climate change.
